snippet.textDisplay: I like it. Beautiful music. Little confused on the choice of costume though. I understand two of them but the scenes with the feather headdress throws me. I see the direction with the bohemian look, but using the turquoise and feathers makes it very Native American or even parts of South American culture. It's misplaced. I also need to point out-being Apache...this obsession people have with the feather headdresses is really annoying and offensive. They look cool, we get it. But it's a sacred item only worn for very specific purposes and not meant for women to wear. I get that some people who did not grow up in certain Native cultures don't understand that, and that's okay. But to give you some perspective on what it's like watching musicians and models use them in their work: it would be like Catholics watching a model pose in a bikini with a matching pope hat. It's would be offensive to their conservative beliefs. The African American community can claim their rightfully owned corn rows to not be worn by people who aren't black, because it's a huge part of their culture in ways people don't understand. Why can't we have the same respect for Native American culture? Let's put a white person on an NFL logo too and call them the New England Quakers, with a powdered wig and a whip in their hand...you see what I'm saying? We aren't extinct. We are still here. Lindsey wasn't being intentionally disrespectful, but the headpiece- how subtle it might have been, is not for music videos, and it's not for women. I've heard some white people get mad that "their movies" are being remade with characters who were originally white and are now Asian, or African American or Latin. Like the other cultures are stealing their media and culture. Like they're taking over everything they've made....Oh please. You want to talk about taking? Lol. Look, if people who aren't Native want to wear a feather headpiece, make your own. Ours do not belong on your head. My opinion stands on "I Wonder As I Wander" as well. Nonetheless, good job on the nostalgic video Lindsey, you are so talented.
